<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">IUCN Red List Category.</emphasis>
Based on estimates from GeoCAT, the EOO of 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. tsukushiense" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="tsukushiense">
D. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
tsukushiense
</taxonomicName>
is 0.001 km2. The known AOO of 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. tsukushiense" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="tsukushiense">
D. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
tsukushiense
</taxonomicName>
is 4.0 km2. Only 10 individuals are found in the type locality and population size is decreasing because of illegal waste dumping in forests. Therefore, this hybrid should be considered critically endangered (CR), as per the 
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="PhytoKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" refId="B7" refString="IUCN, 2012. Guidelines for application of IUCN Red List criteria at regional and national levels: Version 4.0. Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK." title="Guidelines for application of IUCN Red List criteria at regional and national levels: Version 4.0. Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK." year="2012">IUCN (2012)</bibRefCitation>
criteria. A formal evaluation of endangerment is summarised by the following IUCN hierarchical alphanumeric coding: CR B1ab (i, iv, v)+B2ab (i, iv,v)+C1+C2 a (i, ii) b+D.
</paragraph>
